{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533390"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:35:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:35:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14780"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584698"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:54:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:54:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14780"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14780"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.11,0.2,0.16,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58571"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7471"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14780"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43973"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18283"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58571"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman is conducting research on medieval plague outbreaks in Mongolia. She has discovered detailed village records from the 14th century describing an outbreak with the following characteristics: rapid spread through villages, high mortality rate, and descriptions of painful swellings in victims\u0027 groins and armpits. The records note a concurrent massive die-off of local rodent populations. She has also found evidence of similar outbreaks occurring every 8-10 years in the same region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe records specifically mention that the disease seemed to affect multiple members of the same household within days of each other, and that the swellings (described as \u0027buboes\u0027) were most commonly found in the groin, armpit, or neck. The mortality rate was documented as approximately 60% of affected individuals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely mode of disease transmission in these historical outbreaks?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct contact with contaminated soil","Ingestion of contaminated grain","Aerosol transmission between humans","Contact with infected corpses","Flea bite"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe historical records describe a classic epidemic of bubonic plague caused by \u003Cem\u003EYersinia pestis\u003C/em\u003E. The key epidemiological features include the presence of buboes (swollen lymph nodes), high mortality rate, and association with rodent die-offs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlea bite\u003C/strong\u003E transmission is most consistent with the described pattern. The concurrent rodent deaths suggest a rodent-flea-human transmission cycle, which is characteristic of bubonic plague. Fleas abandon dead rodent hosts to seek human hosts, explaining the pattern of household clusters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect contact with contaminated soil\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain the seasonal pattern, household clustering, or association with rodent deaths. Soil-borne diseases typically show different epidemiological patterns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIngestion of contaminated grain\u003C/strong\u003E would likely result in more widespread, simultaneous outbreaks rather than the household-by-household pattern described. It would also not explain the association with rodent deaths.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAerosol transmission\u003C/strong\u003E between humans would typically result in primary pneumonic plague, which has an even higher mortality rate (near 100%) and different clinical features than those described in the records.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact with infected corpses\u003C/strong\u003E alone cannot explain the initial cases or the association with rodent deaths, though it may have contributed to some disease spread during the outbreak.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the mode of transmission is crucial for interpreting historical plague epidemiology. The pattern of spread, clinical features, and ecological associations (rodent deaths) strongly support flea-borne transmission as the primary mechanism in these outbreaks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Yersinia pestis is primarily transmitted between rodents and humans via infected fleas.","Understanding transmission routes is crucial for interpreting historical epidemiology."],"references":["Barbieri R, Signoli M, Chev\u00e9 D, et al. Yersinia pestis: the Natural History of Plague. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2020;34(1):e00044-19. Published 2020 Dec 9. doi:10.1128/CMR.00044-19"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43973"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14780"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43973"},"attributes":{"create